General '''Cyrus Trapaud''' ([[18 August]] [[1715]]<U+2013>[[3 May]] [[1801]]) was a [[British Army]] officer.  

Trapaud was born in Dublin, the son of a [[Huguenot]] refugee family, and a relative of [[Marshall Turenne]].<ref name="QRS">[http://www.queensroyalsurreys.org.uk/colonels/063.html Queen's Royal Surreys]</ref> He served in the [[Buffs (Royal East Kent Regiment)]], accompanying the regiment to the Netherlands in 1742. As an [[Ensign (rank)|ensign]] at the [[Battle of Dettingen]], 1743, he reputedly saved the life of [[George II of Great Britain|King George II]], whose horse had bolted, and received a promotion as a reward.<ref>[http://www.trapaud.org/plaistow/dwp.htm Trapaud.org] </ref> Trapaud was also present at the battles of [[Battle of Fontenoy]], [[Battle of Falkirk (1746)|Falkirk]] and [[Battle of Culloden|Culloden]].<ref name="QRS"/>

In 1760, Trapaud was made a [[colonel]] in the [[70th Regiment of Foot]]; he was promoted to [[Major General]] in 1762, [[Lieutenant General]] in 1772, and full [[General]] in 1783.<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=UjkX5H98svMC&pg=PA15&lpg=PA15&dq=General+Cyrus+Trapaud&source=web&ots=703a5skw0R&sig=Zlv8qpHAxcsp6ddYmChIpkR8Eac&hl=en#PPA16,M1 ''Historical Records of the British Army (Infantry)'', 1861]</ref>

He was transferred to the [[52nd (Oxfordshire) Regiment of Foot]] in 1778,<ref name="QRS"/>  of which he acted as Colonel.<ref>[http://www.lightinfantry.org.uk/regiments/obli/ox_colonels.htm Light Infantry.org]</ref> On his death in 1801, he was succeeded by [[John Moore (British Army officer)|Sir John Moore]].<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=BtPlGsKKaa8C&pg=PA368&lpg=PA368&dq=%22Cyrus+Trapaud%22&source=web&ots=1tXqRDdX7I&sig=nXu_cQkNmyYp9ACjNh92O2i3ack&hl=en ''Dictionary of National Biography'', p.  368]</ref>

Trapaud was married to Catherine, whose portrait was painted by [[Sir Joshua Reynolds]].  Copies of these, by Edward Fisher, are held by the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]].<ref>[http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/person.asp?LinkID=mp50824 National Portrait Gallery]</ref> Trapaud's brother was deputy Governor of [[Fort Augustus]].<ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=kQ9yVsm3mFgC&pg=PA106&lpg=PA106&dq=%22Cyrus+Trapaud%22&source=web&ots=ji6v74KHCl&sig=TeElAslZet4qjPUBEfmbZze5ZOw&hl=en#PPA106,M1 James Boswell, ''The Journal of a Tour to the Hebrides with Samuel Johnson'']</ref>

